0:{"rsc":["$","$1","c",{"children":[["$","article",null,{"className":"bg-slate-50 min-h-screen py-12","children":[["$","script",null,{"type":"application/ld+json","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"{\"@context\":\"https://schema.org\",\"@type\":\"Article\",\"headline\":\"Jamaica Customs Duty Rates Explained: What You Will Pay on Online Shopping in 2026\",\"image\":[\"https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1450101499163-c8848c66ca85?w=800&q=80\"],\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-18T05:00:00.000Z\",\"dateModified\":\"2026-03-18T05:00:00.000Z\",\"author\":[{\"@type\":\"Organization\",\"name\":\"DealPlug Jamaica\",\"url\":\"https://dealplugjamaica.com\"}],\"description\":\"A plain-English breakdown of Jamaica's import duty rates, GCT, the $100 de minimis rule, and exactly what you will owe when your Temu or AliExpress package exceeds the threshold.\"}"}}],["$","script",null,{"type":"application/ld+json","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"{\"@context\":\"https://schema.org\",\"@type\":\"BreadcrumbList\",\"itemListElement\":[{\"@type\":\"ListItem\",\"position\":1,\"name\":\"Home\",\"item\":\"https://dealplugjamaica.com\"},{\"@type\":\"ListItem\",\"position\":2,\"name\":\"Blog\",\"item\":\"https://dealplugjamaica.com/blog\"},{\"@type\":\"ListItem\",\"position\":3,\"name\":\"Jamaica Customs Duty Rates Explained: What You Will Pay on Online Shopping in 2026\",\"item\":\"https://dealplugjamaica.com/blog/jamaica-customs-duty-rates-guide\"}]}"}}],["$","div",null,{"className":"max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4","children":[["$","nav",null,{"className":"text-sm font-medium text-slate-500 mb-8 flex items-center gap-2","children":[["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/","className":"hover:text-gold transition-colors","children":"Home"}],["$","span",null,{"children":"/"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-slate-900 truncate max-w-xs","children":"Jamaica Customs Duty Rates Explained: What You Will Pay on Online Shopping in 2026"}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"bg-white rounded-3xl shadow-lg border border-slate-100 overflow-hidden mb-12","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"relative h-64 md:h-96 w-full bg-slate-200","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"absolute top-6 left-6 z-10 bg-white/90 backdrop-blur-sm text-slate-800 text-sm font-bold px-4 py-2 rounded-full shadow-md","children":"Guide"}],["$","$L3",null,{"src":"https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1450101499163-c8848c66ca85?w=800&q=80","alt":"Jamaica Customs Duty Rates Explained: What You Will Pay on Online Shopping in 2026","fill":true,"priority":true,"sizes":"(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 800px","className":"object-cover"}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"p-8 md:p-12","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex gap-4 text-sm text-slate-500 font-medium mb-6","children":[["$","time",null,{"dateTime":"2026-03-18T05:00:00.000Z","children":"Mar 18, 2026"}],["$","span",null,{"children":"•"}],["$","span",null,{"children":["9 min"," read"]}]]}],["$","h1",null,{"className":"text-4xl md:text-5xl font-extrabold font-jakarta mb-8 text-slate-900 leading-tight","children":"Jamaica Customs Duty Rates Explained: What You Will Pay on Online Shopping in 2026"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"prose prose-lg prose-slate max-w-none prose-headings:font-jakarta prose-headings:font-extrabold prose-a:text-green hover:prose-a:text-emerald-700","children":[["$","p","0",{"className":"mb-6 leading-relaxed text-slate-700 border-l-4 border-transparent hover:border-gold pl-4 transition-colors","children":"Understanding Jamaica's import duty system is the single most important piece of financial knowledge for any Jamaican who shops online. Get it wrong and a US$120 purchase can cost you US$200+ by the time it clears customs. Get it right and you can shop freely under the duty-free threshold and save thousands of dollars a year. Here is a complete, plain-English guide."}],"$L4","$L5","$L6","$L7","$L8","$L9","$La","$Lb","$Lc","$Ld","$Le","$Lf","$L10","$L11"]}],"$L12"]}]]}]]}]]}],["$L13"],"$L14"]}],"isPartial":false,"staleTime":300,"varyParams":null,"buildId":"zygj5-HufB_6PwBOvilB_"}
4:["$","h2","1",{"className":"text-2xl mt-12 mb-6","children":"The De Minimis Threshold: The Golden Rule"}]
5:["$","p","2",{"className":"mb-6 leading-relaxed text-slate-700 border-l-4 border-transparent hover:border-gold pl-4 transition-colors","children":"Jamaica's de minimis threshold — the value below which imports are completely duty-free — is currently US$100 (Free on Board / FOB value). FOB value means the cost of the goods only, excluding insurance and freight charges. This threshold applies per individual package per addressee. If your package's declared FOB value is US$100 or less, no import duties, no GCT, and no customs processing fees apply. The package passes through Customs automatically and goes straight to your freight forwarder's local facility."}]
6:["$","h2","3",{"className":"text-2xl mt-12 mb-6","children":"What Happens When You Exceed US$100?"}]
7:["$","p","4",{"className":"mb-6 leading-relaxed text-slate-700 border-l-4 border-transparent hover:border-gold pl-4 transition-colors","children":"If your package exceeds the US$100 FOB threshold, the Jamaica Customs Agency (JCA) assesses duties on the full CIF value — that is, Cost + Insurance + Freight. This is an important distinction: even though the de minimis check uses FOB value, the duty calculation uses CIF value, which is always higher because it includes the cost of shipping. A US$110 item with US$8 in freight becomes a US$118 CIF value on which duties are calculated."}]
8:["$","h2","5",{"className":"text-2xl mt-12 mb-6","children":"Import Duty Rates by Product Category"}]
9:["$","p","6",{"className":"mb-6 leading-relaxed text-slate-700 border-l-4 border-transparent hover:border-gold pl-4 transition-colors","children":"Jamaica's import duty rates vary significantly by product category. Electronics (phones, tablets, laptops, TVs): 0-5% customs duty. However, a Stamp Duty of 20% and the standard 15% GCT still apply, making the effective all-in rate roughly 35-40% above the CIF value. Clothing and footwear: 20% customs duty + 15% GCT = ~38% effective rate. Kitchen appliances (air fryers, blenders, etc.): 20% customs duty + 15% GCT = ~38%. Toys and games: 20% + 15% GCT. Jewellery: 20% + 15% GCT. Furniture: 20% + 15% GCT."}]
a:["$","h2","7",{"className":"text-2xl mt-12 mb-6","children":"General Consumption Tax (GCT) on Imports"}]
b:["$","p","8",{"className":"mb-6 leading-relaxed text-slate-700 border-l-4 border-transparent hover:border-gold pl-4 transition-colors","children":"GCT is Jamaica's equivalent of Value Added Tax (VAT) and is charged at a flat 15% rate on virtually all imported goods that exceed the de minimis threshold. It is calculated on top of the duty-inclusive value: GCT = 15% × (CIF Value + Import Duty). This means GCT compounds on top of the import duty, not just the base CIF value. For a US$150 item with a 20% duty rate, the calculation looks like this: CIF = US$158 (including freight). Import Duty = 20% × US$158 = US$31.60. GCT = 15% × (US$158 + US$31.60) = US$28.44. Total customs charges = US$60.04. Total all-in cost = US$210.04 — for a US$150 item."}]
c:["$","h2","9",{"className":"text-2xl mt-12 mb-6","children":"How Customs Assesses Value: What If the Seller Under-Declares?"}]
d:["$","p","10",{"className":"mb-6 leading-relaxed text-slate-700 border-l-4 border-transparent hover:border-gold pl-4 transition-colors","children":"The Jamaica Customs Agency uses the WTO Agreement on Customs Valuation, which mandates that customs officers can use published retail transaction prices from a global database to independently verify declared values. If a seller declares a US$200 smartphone as a US$30 gift, a JCA officer will flag the package, look up the phone's standard market value, and assess duties on the higher figure. The importer (you) will be notified of the re-assessment and can either pay the revised duty or formally dispute it. Penalties for knowingly participating in value misdeclaration can include forfeiture of the goods and fines."}]
e:["$","h2","11",{"className":"text-2xl mt-12 mb-6","children":"Practical Tips for Staying Compliant and Saving Money"}]
f:["$","p","12",{"className":"mb-6 leading-relaxed text-slate-700 border-l-4 border-transparent hover:border-gold pl-4 transition-colors","children":"The most effective strategy is simply to keep all individual package FOB values at US$99 or below. Split your orders into separate shipments if needed. For items that will inevitably exceed $100 (larger appliances, furniture, etc.), budget the true all-in cost before you order. Use the formula: Total Cost = CIF Value × 1.38 (for 20% duty + 15% GCT). So a US$300 air conditioner at CIF of US$320 will cost approximately US$441.60 after all duties — still potentially less than the Jamaican retail price, but you need to know this before you commit."}]
10:["$","h2","13",{"className":"text-2xl mt-12 mb-6","children":"How to Dispute a Customs Assessment"}]
11:["$","p","14",{"className":"mb-6 leading-relaxed text-slate-700 border-l-4 border-transparent hover:border-gold pl-4 transition-colors","children":"If you believe the JCA has over-assessed your package's value, you have the right to formally dispute it. Contact the JCA office at Kingston Freeport (for air cargo) or the relevant port of entry. Submit the original purchase invoice or Temu/AliExpress order confirmation showing the actual transaction price. The JCA will review the transaction evidence and, if it supports a lower value, revise the assessment. This process can take several days and requires you to leave the package in bond during the dispute, but for high-value items it is absolutely worth pursuing."}]
